---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="Contract-Driven Development — Eidos AGI"
  description="Contracts define what we want. Skills define how. Only one survives as AI improves."
>
    <article class="prose-page">
      <header class="page-hero">
        <h1>Contracts, Not Skills</h1>
        <p class="subtitle">The right primitive for AI systems.</p>
      </header>

      <section class="content-section">
        <p>The AI ecosystem is building skills — step-by-step instructions that tell models how to accomplish goals. Skills work today. They compensate for what the model can't figure out on its own.</p>
        <p>But skills are written based on today's weaknesses. Imagine writing a skills file for GPT-3 two years ago. It would be extremely verbose — every step spelled out, every edge case handled, every format detail specified. Today's models need less of that. Tomorrow's models need even less.</p>
        <p><strong>Skills are technical debt that accrues as models improve.</strong> Every step-by-step instruction is a bet that future models will be as limited as today's. That bet has never paid off.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>What survives</h2>
        <p>A contract defines what we want — the end state, the constraints, the guardrails. It does not define how to get there, what order to do things, or what tools to use.</p>
        <p>Compare these two ways of saying "improve a software project":</p>

        <div class="cdd-compare">
          <div class="cdd-compare-item cdd-compare-skill">
            <div class="cdd-compare-label">A skill <span class="cdd-compare-meta">150 lines</span></div>
            <pre><code>Step 1: Read CLAUDE.md to understand the project
Step 2: Read .visionlog/vision.md for stated purpose
Step 3: Detect project type (forge vs software)
  - Knowledge forge: skip performance, security
  - Software: check builds, tests, dependencies
Step 4: Score each dimension 1-10 using this rubric:
  | Dimension | 1 (broken) | 5 (rough) | 10 (done) |
  | Reliability | crashes | happy path | battle-tested |
  | Performance | unusable | acceptable | profiled |
  ...eight more dimensions with calibration...
Step 5: Pick the highest-impact gap
Step 6: Make the fix. Read before writing.
Step 7: Run tests. Verify the build.
Step 8: Write the snapshot to improvements/
  Use this exact JSON format:
  &#123; "date": "...", "scores": &#123;...&#125;, ... &#125;</code></pre>
          </div>
          <div class="cdd-compare-item cdd-compare-contract">
            <div class="cdd-compare-label">A contract <span class="cdd-compare-meta">10 lines</span></div>
            <pre><code>&#123;
  "goal": "Leave the project measurably better",
  "output": "improvement-snapshot.schema.json",
  "constraints": [
    "Every score cites specific evidence",
    "Fix the highest-impact gap, not easiest",
    "Never violate the project's guardrails",
    "Record every run"
  ]
&#125;</code></pre>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p>The skill says <em>how</em>. The contract says <em>what</em>. Models get better at <em>how</em> every six months. <em>What</em> doesn't change.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>The bitter lesson</h2>
        <p>Richard Sutton's greatest contribution to computer science: general methods that leverage computation always beat hand-crafted human knowledge as compute scales.</p>
        <p>We teach a computer to play chess by giving it the rules of chess (a contract) and a goal (win). We don't give it opening theory, middlegame strategy, or endgame technique. That's a skill. The system that learned to play chess without human strategy knowledge destroyed the one built on decades of human expertise.</p>
        <p>Skills are chess strategy books. Contracts are the rules of chess. One decays with every improvement in reasoning. The other is permanent.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>In practice</h2>
        <p>Three contracts that replace three skills files:</p>

        <div class="cdd-contracts-list">
          <div class="cdd-contract-item"><strong>code-review.schema.json</strong> — defines what a reviewed file looks like: findings with severity, line numbers, and fixes. The model decides how to review. The contract defines what "reviewed" means.</div>
          <div class="cdd-contract-item"><strong>deployment-record.schema.json</strong> — defines what a successful deployment looks like: service name, SHA, health check status, rollback plan. The model decides how to deploy. The contract defines what "deployed" means.</div>
          <div class="cdd-contract-item"><strong>improvement-snapshot.schema.json</strong> — defines what a better project looks like: scores across 10 dimensions with evidence, delta from last run, next priority. The model decides how to improve. The contract defines what "better" means.</div>
        </div>

        <p>Each contract is a JSON Schema. Any model — current or future — reads the schema and produces conforming output. A better model produces a sharper code review, a more thorough deployment check, a more insightful improvement. But the output still conforms to the same schema. The contract is the stable interface between human intent and AI capability.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>The transition</h2>
        <p>You don't have to abandon skills today. Current models still benefit from guidance. The shift is:</p>
        <ol class="cdd-transition-steps">
          <li><strong>Define the contract first.</strong> What does the output look like? Write the JSON Schema.</li>
          <li><strong>Write the skill second.</strong> Only if the model can't meet the contract from the schema alone.</li>
          <li><strong>Test without the skill periodically.</strong> Give the model just the contract. If the output conforms, the skill is done.</li>
          <li><strong>Let skills decay.</strong> Don't maintain them. They're temporary bridges.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>The <code>contracts/</code> directory is permanent infrastructure. The <code>skills/</code> directory is a construction site that eventually gets torn down.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>The confidence model</h2>
        <p>Every fact an agent depends on carries a confidence level. The readiness of a system is the lowest confidence of its parts. One "unknown" means the whole system is not production-ready.</p>
        <table class="cdd-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Level</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Can build on?</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td class="cdd-level cdd-proven">proven</td><td>Tested in production, confirmed</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="cdd-level cdd-tested">tested</td><td>Validated against real system</td><td>Yes, with monitoring</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="cdd-level cdd-researched">researched</td><td>From docs, not verified</td><td>Verify first</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="cdd-level cdd-inferred">inferred</td><td>Guessed from similar systems</td><td>No — verify</td></tr>
            <tr><td class="cdd-level cdd-unknown">unknown</td><td>No information</td><td>No — discover</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <h2>The tools</h2>
        <div class="cdd-trio">
          <div class="cdd-trio-item">
            <h3>visionlog</h3>
            <p>Records the contracts — guardrails, goals, ADRs.</p>
            <code>pip install visionlog-md</code>
          </div>
          <div class="cdd-trio-item">
            <h3>research.md</h3>
            <p>Earns decisions with evidence before they become contracts.</p>
            <code>pip install research-md</code>
          </div>
          <div class="cdd-trio-item">
            <h3>ike.md</h3>
            <p>Executes tasks within the contracts.</p>
            <code>pip install ike-md</code>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="content-section">
        <p class="cdd-closing">Contracts define what we want, not how to deliver it. That's the primitive that survives AGI.</p>
      </section>

      <div class="related">
        <span class="related-label">Related</span>
        <div class="related-links">
          <a href="/trilogy">The Trilogy</a>
          <a href="/forges">Forges</a>
          <a href="/memory">Memory</a>
          <a href="/eidos">Eidos</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>
</Base>

<style is:global>
  .cdd-compare { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: var(--space-4); margin: var(--space-8) 0; }
  .cdd-compare-item { border-radius: var(--radius-md); overflow: hidden; }
  .cdd-compare-label { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-xs); padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); font-weight: var(--weight-medium); }
  .cdd-compare-meta { opacity: 0.5; margin-left: var(--space-2); }
  .cdd-compare-skill .cdd-compare-label { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-danger) 15%, transparent); color: var(--color-danger); }
  .cdd-compare-contract .cdd-compare-label { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-command) 15%, transparent); color: var(--color-command); }
  .cdd-compare-item pre { margin: 0; padding: var(--space-4); background: var(--color-surface); font-size: var(--text-xs); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed); }
  .cdd-compare-item code { color: var(--color-muted); }
  .cdd-contracts-list { margin: var(--space-6) 0; }
  .cdd-contract-item { font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted); padding: var(--space-3) 0; border-bottom: var(--border-width) solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-muted) 10%, transparent); }
  .cdd-contract-item strong { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-xs); color: var(--color-primary); }
  .cdd-transition-steps { padding-left: var(--space-6); }
  .cdd-transition-steps li { font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted); padding: var(--space-2) 0; line-height: var(--leading-normal); }
  .cdd-table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: var(--text-sm); margin: var(--space-6) 0; }
  .cdd-table th { text-align: left; font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-xs); color: var(--color-muted); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.06em; padding: var(--space-2) var(--space-3); border-bottom: 2px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-muted) 20%, transparent); }
  .cdd-table td { padding: var(--space-2) var(--space-3); border-bottom: var(--border-width) solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-muted) 10%, transparent); color: var(--color-muted); }
  .cdd-level { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-weight: var(--weight-medium); }
  .cdd-proven { color: var(--color-command); }
  .cdd-tested { color: var(--color-secondary); }
  .cdd-researched { color: var(--color-primary); }
  .cdd-inferred { color: var(--color-muted); }
  .cdd-unknown { color: var(--color-danger); }
  .cdd-trio { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr); gap: var(--space-4); margin-top: var(--space-6); }
  .cdd-trio-item { background: var(--color-surface); padding: var(--space-6); border-radius: var(--radius-md); }
  .cdd-trio-item h3 { color: var(--color-primary); margin-bottom: var(--space-2); }
  .cdd-trio-item p { font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted); margin-bottom: var(--space-3); }
  .cdd-trio-item code { font-size: var(--text-xs); color: var(--color-command); }
  .cdd-closing { font-size: var(--text-md); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed); }
  @media (max-width: 768px) { .cdd-compare { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } .cdd-trio { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } .cdd-table { font-size: var(--text-xs); } }
</style>
